# Image View

The `Dali::Ui::ImageView` control is a `dali-ui` application layer object model that displays images from various sources. It offers extensive control over image loading, display, and manipulation, ensuring efficient and customizable image presentation within your `dali-ui` applications.

## Table of Contents

*   [Creating an ImageView](#creating-an-imageview)
*   [Loading and Displaying Images](#loading-and-displaying-images)
*   [Image Sizing and Fitting](#image-sizing-and-fitting)
*   [Image Masking](#image-masking)
*   [N-Patch Images](#n-patch-images)
*   [Image Loading and Performance Policies](#image-loading-and-performance-policies)
*   [Image Colorization](#image-colorization)
*   [Retrieving Image Information](#retrieving-image-information)

## Creating an ImageView

You can create an `ImageView` instance using its default constructor or the `New()` static method. Both methods provide a handle to a newly created `ImageView`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui/dali-ui.h>

// Using the default constructor
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView1;

// Using the static New() method
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView2 = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
```

To integrate an `ImageView` into your application, add it to the view hierarchy, for example, by adding it to a `Dali::Ui::View` or `Dali::Ui::Stage`.

```cpp
// Assuming `parentView` is an existing Dali::Ui::View
Dali::Ui::View parentView = Dali::Ui::View::New();
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
parentView.Add(imageView);
```

## Loading and Displaying Images

The `ImageView` can load and display images from a local file path. You can also specify a placeholder image to be displayed while the main image is loading.

### Setting the Image Resource

Use `SetResourceUrl()` to specify the path to the image file.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("image_path.png");
// Add imageView to the view hierarchy to display the image
```

### Using a Placeholder Image

To provide a visual cue during image loading, set a `PlaceholderUrl()`:

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("large_image.jpg");
imageView.SetPlaceholderUrl("loading_indicator.png");
```

### Reloading an Image

If the image source changes or you need to force a reload, call `Reload()`:

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("updated_image.png");
imageView.Reload();
```

### Resource Ready Signal

The `ResourceReadySignal()` emits when the image resource has finished loading. This is useful for performing actions once the image is ready for display.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/signals/connection-tracker.h>
#include <dali/integration-api/debug.h>

class MyImageController : public Dali::ConnectionTracker
{
public:
  void OnImageReady(Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView)
  {
    // Image is loaded and ready
    DALI_LOG_RELEASE_INFO("Image loaded: %s\n", imageView.GetResourceUrl().c_str());
  }

  void SetupImageView(Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView)
  {
    imageView.ResourceReadySignal().Connect(this, &MyImageController::OnImageReady);
    imageView.SetResourceUrl("my_image.png");
  }
};
```

## Image Sizing and Fitting

Control how the image is scaled and positioned within the `ImageView`'s boundaries using desired dimensions, fitting modes, and pixel areas.

### Setting Desired Dimensions

You can specify the desired width and height for the image. The `ImageView` will attempt to load the image at these dimensions, potentially scaling it.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("my_image.jpg")
         .SetDesiredWidth(200)
         .SetDesiredHeight(150);
```

You can also enable `ImageLoadWithViewSize` to make the image load with the current size of the view.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("my_image.jpg")
         .SetImageLoadWithViewSize(true);
```

### Image Fitting Mode

The `SetFittingMode()` method determines how the image content fits into the `ImageView`'s area. Available modes include `Dali::Image::FittingMode::SHRINK_TO_FIT`, `Dali::Image::FittingMode::RESIZE_TO_FIT`, and `Dali::Image::FittingMode::FILL`.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/images/image.h> // For Dali::Image::FittingMode

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("my_image.png")
         .SetFittingMode(Dali::Image::FittingMode::SHRINK_TO_FIT);
```

### Specifying Pixel Area

Use `SetPixelArea()` to define a specific rectangular area of the source image to display. The `Vector4` argument represents `(x, y, width, height)` as a normalized range (0.0 to 1.0) of the original image dimensions.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/math/vector4.h>

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
// Display the top-left quarter of the image
imageView.SetResourceUrl("my_large_image.png")
         .SetPixelArea(Dali::Vector4(0.0f, 0.0f, 0.5f, 0.5f));
```

## Image Masking

The `ImageView` supports alpha masking to create complex shapes or effects for displayed images.

### Applying an Alpha Mask

Use `SetAlphaMaskUrl()` to specify an image that will act as an alpha mask. The alpha channel of the mask image determines the transparency of the main image.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("content_image.png")
         .SetAlphaMaskUrl("mask_image.png");
```

### Masking Mode

The `SetMaskingMode()` method controls when the masking operation is applied. `Dali::Image::MaskingType::ON_RENDERING` applies the mask at render time, while `Dali::Image::MaskingType::ON_LOADING` applies it when the image is loaded.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/images/image.h> // For Dali::Image::MaskingType

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("content_image.png")
         .SetAlphaMaskUrl("mask_image.png")
         .SetMaskingMode(Dali::Image::MaskingType::ON_RENDERING);
```

### Cropping to Mask

When `SetCropToMask(true)` is set, the `ImageView` will crop its content to the bounding box of the alpha mask.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("content_image.png")
         .SetAlphaMaskUrl("mask_image.png")
         .SetCropToMask(true);
```

## N-Patch Images

N-patch images are useful for creating scalable UI elements that stretch certain areas while preserving corners and edges.

### Setting N-Patch Border

The `SetNPatchBorder()` method defines the border of an N-patch image. The `Vector4` argument specifies `(left, right, bottom, top)` border widths in pixels. These areas will not be scaled.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/math/vector4.h>

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("n_patch_button.png")
         .SetNPatchBorder(Dali::Vector4(10.0f, 10.0f, 10.0f, 10.0f)); // 10px border on all sides
```

### Border Only N-Patch

When `SetNPatchBorderOnly(true)` is enabled, only the border areas of the N-patch image are rendered, effectively making the center transparent.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("n_patch_frame.png")
         .SetNPatchBorder(Dali::Vector4(5.0f, 5.0f, 5.0f, 5.0f))
         .SetNPatchBorderOnly(true);
```

## Image Loading and Performance Policies

Optimize image loading behavior and performance with various policies, including synchronous loading, fast-track uploading, and orientation correction.

### Load and Release Policies

`SetLoadPolicy()` and `SetReleasePolicy()` control when image resources are loaded and released. This can impact memory usage and performance. Options include `Dali::Image::LoadPolicy::IMMEDIATE` and `Dali::Image::LoadPolicy::ON_DEMAND` for loading, and `Dali::Image::ReleasePolicy::IMMEDIATE` and `Dali::Image::ReleasePolicy::LAZY` for releasing.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/images/image.h> // For Dali::Image::LoadPolicy, Dali::Image::ReleasePolicy

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("background.jpg")
         .SetLoadPolicy(Dali::Image::LoadPolicy::ON_DEMAND)
         .SetReleasePolicy(Dali::Image::ReleasePolicy::LAZY);
```

### Synchronous Loading

By default, image loading is asynchronous. Set `SetSynchronousLoading(true)` to force the image to load synchronously, blocking the UI thread until the image is ready. Use with caution for small images or when immediate display is critical.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("icon.png")
         .SetSynchronousLoading(true);
```

### Fast Track Upload

Enable `SetFastTrackUpload(true)` for potentially faster image uploads to the GPU, especially for larger images.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("high_res_image.jpg")
         .SetFastTrackUpload(true);
```

### Orientation Correction

`SetOrientationCorrection(true)` enables automatic rotation of the image based on its EXIF metadata.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("camera_image.jpg")
         .SetOrientationCorrection(true);
```

### Pre-Multiplied Alpha

`SetPreMultipliedAlpha(true)` specifies whether the image's color channels are pre-multiplied by its alpha channel. This can affect how the image blends with other elements.

```cpp
Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("transparent_logo.png")
         .SetPreMultipliedAlpha(true);
```

### Sampling Mode

The `SetSamplingMode()` method controls the image sampling algorithm when scaling. Options include `Dali::Image::SamplingMode::BOX`, `Dali::Image::SamplingMode::LINEAR`, and `Dali::Image::SamplingMode::BOX_THEN_LINEAR`.

```cpp
#include <dali/public-api/images/image.h> // For Dali::Image::SamplingMode

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("scaled_artwork.png")
         .SetSamplingMode(Dali::Image::SamplingMode::LINEAR);
```

## Image Colorization

You can apply a tint or color overlay to the displayed image using `SetImageColor()`.

```cpp
#include <dali-ui-foundation/public-api/colors/ui-color.h> // For UiColor

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("grayscale_image.png")
         .SetImageColor(Dali::Ui::UiColor::RED); // Tint the image red
```

## Retrieving Image Information

Query the `ImageView` to retrieve various properties of the loaded image or the `ImageView` itself.

```cpp
#include <dali/integration-api/debug.h>
#include <dali/public-api/images/image.h>

Dali::Ui::ImageView imageView = Dali::Ui::ImageView::New();
imageView.SetResourceUrl("info_image.png")
         .SetDesiredWidth(300)
         .SetFittingMode(Dali::Image::FittingMode::RESIZE_TO_FIT);

// Retrieve image properties
Dali::String imageUrl = imageView.GetResourceUrl();
int desiredWidth = imageView.GetDesiredWidth();
Dali::Image::FittingMode fittingMode = imageView.GetFittingMode();
Dali::Ui::Visual::ResourceStatus loadingStatus = imageView.GetLoadingStatus();

DALI_LOG_RELEASE_INFO("Image URL: %s, Desired Width: %d, Fitting Mode: %d, Loading Status: %d\n",
                      imageUrl.c_str(),
                      desiredWidth,
                      static_cast<int>(fittingMode),
                      static_cast<int>(loadingStatus));
```
